{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644750"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18060"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18060"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.05,0.85,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76273"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5739"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76273"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProfessional boundaries are essential ethical guidelines that define appropriate behaviour between healthcare providers and patients. These boundaries help maintain therapeutic relationships and protect both parties. There are a number of potential boundary violations in medical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most clearly a boundary violation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accepting expensive gifts from grateful patients","Sharing personal contact details with patients","Providing regular medical care to close friends","Pursuing a romantic relationship with a current patient","Discussing personal problems during consultations"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA boundary violation occurs when a healthcare provider crosses professional limits that should exist in the therapeutic relationship. \u003Cstrong\u003EPursuing a romantic relationship with a current patient\u003C/strong\u003E represents a serious boundary violation as it compromises professional objectivity and exploits the inherent power imbalance in the therapeutic relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent concerning behaviours that may constitute violations depending on context:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccepting expensive gifts from grateful patients\u003C/strong\u003E may constitute a violation if the gift is of significant value or creates a sense of obligation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing personal contact details with patients\u003C/strong\u003E breaches professional boundaries and may lead to inappropriate contact outside of the therapeutic relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding regular medical care to close friends\u003C/strong\u003E risks compromising clinical objectivity and may blur the lines between professional and personal relationships.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussing personal problems during consultations\u003C/strong\u003E represents inappropriate self-disclosure that shifts focus away from patient care and their therapeutic needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinction is between boundary crossings, which may be harmless or even therapeutic in certain contexts, versus boundary violations which are always harmful and unethical. Violations typically involve exploitation of the professional relationship for personal gain or gratification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Professional boundaries protect both patients and healthcare providers by maintaining appropriate therapeutic relationships.","Boundary violations occur when healthcare providers breach the limits of appropriate professional conduct.","Common boundary violations include financial, emotional, physical, and social transgressions in the doctor-patient relationship."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18060"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T17:45:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T17:45:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76273"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdA